table(iris$Species)
## 
##     setosa versicolor  virginica 
##         50         50         50
### Create training and testing Dataset
inTrain <-createDataPartition(y=iris$Species, p=0.7, list=FALSE)
training <-iris[inTrain,]
testing<-iris[-inTrain,]

modFit<-train(Species~., method = "rpart", data=training)
print(modFit$finalModel)
## n= 105 
## 
## node), split, n, loss, yval, (yprob)
##       * denotes terminal node
## 
## 1) root 105 70 setosa (0.33333333 0.33333333 0.33333333)  
##   2) Petal.Length< 2.6 35  0 setosa (1.00000000 0.00000000 0.00000000) *
##   3) Petal.Length>=2.6 70 35 versicolor (0.00000000 0.50000000 0.50000000)  
##     6) Petal.Width< 1.75 37  3 versicolor (0.00000000 0.91891892 0.08108108) *
##     7) Petal.Width>=1.75 33  1 virginica (0.00000000 0.03030303 0.96969697) *
fancyRpartPlot(modFit$finalModel)

# predict new values
prediction<-predict(modFit, newdata=testing)
# summarize accuracy
table(prediction, testing$Species)

##   setosa         15          0         0

Bagging

Bagging or bootstrap aggregation is a simple method to take samples from your test data set to improve the model. The predictions are avergaged to give a better performing model.

glimpse(ozone)
## Observations: 111
## Variables: 4
## $ ozone       <dbl> 41, 36, 12, 18, 23, 19, 8, 16, 11, 14, 18, 14, 34,...
## $ radiation   <int> 190, 118, 149, 313, 299, 99, 19, 256, 290, 274, 65...
## $ temperature <int> 67, 72, 74, 62, 65, 59, 61, 69, 66, 68, 58, 64, 66...
## $ wind        <dbl> 7.4, 8.0, 12.6, 11.5, 8.6, 13.8, 20.1, 9.7, 9.2, 1...
predictors =  data.frame(ozone=ozone$ozone)
temperature  = ozone$temperature
treebag <- bag(predictors, temperature, B=10, bagControl=bagControl(fit=ctreeBag$fit,
             predict = ctreeBag$pred, aggregate = ctreeBag$aggregate))
## Warning: executing %dopar% sequentially: no parallel backend registered
plot(ozone$ozone,temperature,col="green",pch=19)
points(ozone$ozone,predict(treebag$fits[[1]]$fit,predictors),pch=19,col="red")
points(ozone$ozone,predict(treebag,predictors),pch=19,col="blue")
